Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

records.addlTxt: $650 cash already posted. No contact with Victim 1 or address on complaint. The above no contact shall have the exception that the defendant may have a one time contact at the residence with Law Enforcement for property retrieval.

3:38 PM Defendant Jaden William Nelson appeared by video, in custody.  Attorney Ryan Anthony Reid in court for Jaden William Nelson.  Prosecuting attorney Allison E. Cogbill in court for the State of Wisconsin. State notes requests for no contact with address on complaint. Defendant's alternate address confirmed. Attorney/Defendant acknowledges receipt of the complaint, waives a formal reading, enters pleas of not guilty to the misdemeanor count(s), and requests a preliminary hearing. State asks for $1500 cash bail. No contact with Victim 1 or address on ID Key. Does not have any FTAs. Notes that he was ordered to not have contact with victim 1 but continued to contact and threaten victim 1. Notes that he had previously posted $650 to get out on other file. Attorney Reid asks for signature bond or low cash bond, does not qualify for PD, is member of labor union and has employment, has family and a child in the area. Has one prior conviction in only a CT file.
Court orders $1000 cash. Apply money already posted ($650) towards $1000. No contact with Victim 1 or address on the complaint. The above no contact shall have the exception that the defendant may have a one time contact at the residence with Law Enforcement for property retrieval. 
Defendant would like to waive time limits to allow for time to retain counsel. Court accepts waiver as knowingly and voluntarily made.
Preliminary hearing scheduled for October 26, 2022 at 08:45 am.
Status conference scheduled for October 24, 2022 at 03:00 pm.
